# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2nd-continental-artillery-regiment
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] The **1st Canadian Regiment** (1775–1781) was an Extra Continental regiment of the American Patriots' Continental Army, consisting primarily of volunteers from the Province of Quebec.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] The 1st was raised by James Livingston to support Patriot efforts in the American Revolutionary War during the invasion of Quebec.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] Livingston, who was born in New York and living in Quebec, recruited men from Chambly, Quebec as early as September 1775, but a formal regimental designation was made by Richard Montgomery on November 20, 1775, with recognition by the Second Continental Congress following on January 8, 1776.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] The regiment, which never approached its authorized size of 1,000 men, saw action primarily in the Canadian theater and New York, and was disbanded on January 1, 1781, at King's Ferry, New York.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] In September 1775, militia forces from New York and other colonies under the command of Philip Schuyler and Richard Montgomery crossed into Quebec with the aim of driving British military forces from Montreal and Quebec City.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] Guy Carleton, the British governor and military commander, had fortified Fort Saint-Jean as the primary defense of Montreal.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] The colonial forces, preparing to besiege the fort, sought local support.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] James Livingston, a grain merchant living near Chambly, about 10 miles (16 km) from Saint-Jean, raised a local militia, which in October assisted in the siege and capture of Fort Chambly, and the capture of supplies intended for the besieged moving on the Richelieu River.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] Following the fall of Montreal, Livingston was authorized by Montgomery on November 20 to raise a regiment to assist in the coming assault on Quebec City.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] In eight days he raised approximately 200 men.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] The regiment received formal recognition from the Second Continental Congress on January 8, 1776.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] The regiment at first consisted of a mix of Canadiens, Acadiens, and Quebec anglophones.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] Two of Livingston's brothers served in the regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] Richard Livingston was a lieutenant colonel, and Abraham served as a captain.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] When Montgomery's army arrived outside Quebec, the 1st Canadian consisted of two to three hundred Canadiens.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] On December 31, 1775, the regiment was charged with making a diversion at Quebec City's Saint Jean gate, to draw British attention away from the primary attacks, which were led by Benedict Arnold and Richard Montgomery, and were directed at the city's Lower Town.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] The diversions did not work, and the battle ended disastrously for the Americans, with Montgomery killed, Arnold wounded, and about 400 men taken prisoner.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] The remnants of the army, then under Arnold's command, besieged the city until May 1776, when British reinforcements began arriving, forcing the Americans into a panicked retreat.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] The retreat ended at Sorel on May 20, where they were met by reinforcements, and eventually put under the command of General John Sullivan.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] On the night of June 7, 1776, Livingston's regiment was part of a force of about 2,000 under Brigadier General William Thompson that returned from Sorel to Trois-Rivières to drive off what they believed to be 300 to 600 British troops from Quebec.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] When they arrived near Trois-Rivières, they instead found the vanguard of the British counteroffensive, numbering several thousand.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] After a brief skirmish, the Americans forces were broken, and made a disorganized retreat back to Sorel.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] Following this battle, the regiment retreated with the rest of the army to Fort Ticonderoga.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] While the regiment had never been particularly large (Livingston never had more than a few hundred men under arms at any one time), the retreat from Quebec left the regiment much reduced in size, since anyone leaving the province was unlikely to be able to return.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] Following the army's return to Ticonderoga, the regiment was assigned garrison duty in upstate New York, primarily the Mohawk and Schoharie valleys, so that it could be reorganized.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] During this time, Livingston was known to be recruiting in New York City.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] Following Burgoyne's invasion from Quebec in 1777, the regiment was moved to the upper Hudson River valley.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] In August 1777, the regiment was assigned to Benedict Arnold on his expedition in relief of the Siege of Fort Stanwix.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] It then saw service in both Battles of Saratoga as part of Ebenezer Learned's brigade.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] The regiment saw action in the Battle of Rhode Island in 1778.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] For the remainder of the war, the regiment had garrison duty in New York.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] Most notably, Colonel Livingston was in command of Verplanck's Point on the Hudson River in September 1780, and played a crucial role in the unmasking of Benedict Arnold's treachery.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] While on guard duty, his troops fired on the British sloop of war *Vulture*, forcing that vessel to retreat southwards.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] This ship had brought Major John André to meet with General Arnold, who was then in command at West Point.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] Since the ship was driven off, André was forced to attempt travel by land to New York, when he was captured not far from the British lines near Tarrytown with incriminating papers in his possession.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] André was hanged as a spy, and Arnold, his plot discovered, managed to escape to the British lines.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] The regiment was disbanded as part of a major reorganization on January 1, 1781, at King's Ferry, New York.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-canadian-regiment] Members that remained in service were assigned to the 2nd Canadian Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] The **1st Continental Artillery Regiment**, also known as **Harrison's Continental Artillery Regiment**, was authorized on 26 November 1776 as Colonel Charles Harrison's Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] Raised for service during the American Revolutionary War, as originally organized, the regiment comprised 10 artillery companies from Virginia.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] Two of the artillery companies existed since early 1776.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] The regiment was first assigned to the Southern Department, but in March 1778 it was reassigned to General George Washington's main army.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] In August 1779, the unit was renamed the 1st Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] It continued to serve with the main army until April 1780 when it was transferred to the Southern Department.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] In May 1780, Maryland artillery companies formally joined the regiment, making a total of 12 companies.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] In January 1781, the regiment was reorganized with 10 companies.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] Furloughed in the summer of 1783, the regiment was disbanded in November the same year.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] Elements of the regiment fought at Monmouth, Charleston, Camden, Hobkirk's Hill, Eutaw Springs, Yorktown, and Combahee River.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] Harrison's Continental Artillery Regiment became part of the Continental Army on 26 November 1776 with Colonel Charles Harrison as commanding officer.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] The regiment consisted of two companies that were previously in existence.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] In the spring and summer of 1777, the regiment was organized in the strength of 10 companies.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] Harrison's second-in-command was Lieutenant Colonel Edward Carrington.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] The regiment defended Virginia during the remainder of 1777.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] Each artillery company was composed of four officers, one sergeant, four corporals, four bombardiers, eight gunners, and 48 matrosses.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] This differed from the organization in the other artillery regiments.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] The first pre-existing unit was the Virginia State Artillery Company which was authorized on 11 January 1776 and organized in the spring of that year at Williamsburg, Virginia.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] It became part of Harrison's Regiment on 26 November.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] Its original captain was James Innis and its lieutenants were Harrison, Carrington, and Samuel Denney.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] On 19 March, the Continental Congress adopted the first company and authorized a French adventurer, Dohicky Arundel to raise a second Virginia artillery company.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] At some point, Innis transferred to the infantry.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] The second unit became the Virginia Continental Artillery Company which was formed in the summer of 1776 at Williamsburg.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] It joined Harrison's Regiment on 27 November.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] The Virginia artillery played an active role during the Battle of Gwynn's Island in July 1776.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] The only casualty was Arundel, who was killed when his experimental mortar burst.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] The regiment was initially assigned to the Southern Department.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] On 13 March 1778, it was transferred to Washington's main army where elements fought at the Battle of Monmouth on 28 June 1778.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] In that action, Carrington commanded some guns on the left flank under William Alexander, Lord Stirling.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] In 1778, three 106-man Maryland artillery companies joined the regiment on a provisional basis.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] The 1st and 2nd Maryland State Artillery Companies were authorized on 14 January 1776 and the 3rd Company was authorized on 23 October 1776.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] They joined the main army on 22 November 1777 as the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd Maryland Continental Artillery Companies.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] On 9 May 1780, the 1st Maryland Company formally became the 11th Company in the 1st Artillery Regiment and the 2nd and 3rd Maryland Companies became the 12th Company.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] The four artillery regiments received numbers on 10 August 1779.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] Two boards of generals determined that the artillery regiments of Colonels John Lamb and John Crane could not trace continuity from General Henry Knox's old Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] Therefore, Harrison's Regiment became the 1st Continental Artillery Regiment while Lamb's was renamed the 2nd Continental Artillery Regiment and Crane's was numbered the 3rd Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] The regiment of Colonel Thomas Proctor became the 4th Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] Henry Knox, Washington's artillery chief, planned to have four 3-pound or 6-pound cannons attached to each infantry brigade.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] Though Knox preferred the more versatile French 4-pound cannon, he had to abandon a plan to adopt the piece because so much ammunition and material for the other guns were available.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] The army also maintained an artillery park of two 24-pound cannons, four 12-pound cannons, four 8-inch howitzers, eight 5½-inch howitzers, and 10 smaller field guns.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] Knox rotated the artillery companies between infantry brigades, artillery park, and garrisons so the men could be sufficiently trained.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] He discouraged artillery duels and encouraged his artillerymen to reserve their fire for infantry targets.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] This tactic proved very effective at Monmouth.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] The 1st Artillery was reassigned to the Southern Department on 17 April 1780.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] Some units of the regiment fought at the Siege of Charleston in the spring of 1780.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] When General Johann de Kalb was sent south in 1780, Carrington accompanied his division with three artillery companies.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] Harrison arrived and assumed command, due to his superior rank.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] At the Battle of Camden on 16 August 1780, Harrison directed six artillery pieces.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] Two more guns were loaned to Colonel Thomas Sumter's partisans and 10 were left in the rear for lack of horses to pull them.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] The regiment was reorganized to consist of 10 companies on 1 January 1781.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] At the Battle of Hobkirk's Hill on 25 April 1781, Harrison commanded three 6-pound cannons and 40 artillerists.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] At the Battle of Eutaw Springs on 8 September 1781, the Americans had two 3-pounders under Captain William Gaines and two 6-pounders under Captain William Brown.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] During the Siege of Yorktown in the fall of 1781, Captain Whitehead Coleman's company of the 1st Artillery fought under the overall command of Carrington.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] In the Battle of the Combahee River on 27 August 1782, a howitzer and its crew under Captain Smith were captured by the British.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] The regiment was furloughed in the summer of 1783 at Winchester, Virginia and Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-artillery-regiment] It was formally disbanded on 15 November 1783.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The **1st Continental Light Dragoons**, also known as **Bland's Horse**, was a mounted regiment of the Continental Army organized between 13 June and 10 September 1776 in Williamsburg, Virginia.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] It was made up of men from eastern and northern Virginia for service with the Continental Army.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The Revolutionary Virginia Convention held in May 1776 resulted in delegates voting for a resolution to direct Virginia's delegates in Philadelphia to seek independence from the British and form a confederation of the colonies.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] They knew additional military strength was required.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Virginia Governor Patrick Henry authorized Major-Commandant Theodorick Bland to raise a volunteer battalion.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Bland had participated in the expulsion of Royal Governor Dunmore.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The 1st Continental Light Dragoons regiment was first authorized on 8 June 1776 in the Virginia State Troops as the 1st, 2d, 3d, 4th, 5th (Captain Henry "Light Horse Harry" Lee) and 6th Troops of Light Horse.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] On 25 June 1776 it mustered as the Virginia Light Horse Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] It was first adopted by and then accepted into the Continental Army, designated as the 1st Continental Light Dragoons on 25 November 1776.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Six months later, when General George Washington needed cavalry to counter that of the British, the Continental Congress on November 25, 1776 requested that Virginia transfer Major Bland's Light Horse to the Continental Army.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Although reluctant, Virginia acceded to the request.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Bland's Light Horse became the 1st Regiment of Continental Light Dragoons.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Each contained 3 officers, 3 corporals, a drummer, a trumpeter, and 29 privates.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Three quartermasters provided logistical support for the group.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] In March 1777 this 1st Regiment of Continental Light Dragoons — plus the three other regiments — were reorganized, resulting in a slight increase in their numbers.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Each troop consisted of 32 privates, 1 armorer, 1 farrier, 1 trumpeter, 4 corporals, 1 quartermaster sergeant, a drill or an orderly sergeant, a cornet, a lieutenant, and a captain—a total of 280 men and officers.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Whether any of the four regiments of Dragoons was ever at full strength is uncertain.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The 2nd Continental Light Dragoons hailed from Connecticut and was led by Elisha Sheldon.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] It fought with distinction, whether mounted or unmounted, and at war's end had 225 men.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The 3rd Regiment—"Lady Washington's Dragoons"—was also from Virginia.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The 3rd was commanded by Lieutenant-Colonel George Baylor and seconded by Major Alexander Clough, one of George Washington's spies.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The 3rd was the victim of a heinous act of war when they were attacked in their billet and refused quarter in 1778.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The 4th and final regiment drew its membership from Pennsylvania, Maryland, Virginia, and New Jersey.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The 4th suffered great losses at the Battle of Camden.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] So at the very best in 1777, there were 1120 dragoons in the Continental Army, considerably under the 3,000 troops authorized by the Continental Congress.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Officers aside, there were no other mounted troops in the whole continental army.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The English also had limited cavalry, fielding their 16th Queen's Lancers and 17th Regiment of Dragoons.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Light Horse Harry Lee gained national fame from his service with the 1st Continental Regiment at the Battle of Paulus Hook and in the Southern Campaign.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] On 31 March 1777 in General Orders, George Washington named promoted officers of the 1st Light Dragoons.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] On 7 April 1778 Lee's Troop was replaced by Captain Addison Lewis's Troop.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Lee's Troop was expanded into Lee's Legion, designated the 2nd Partisan Corps in 1781.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The 1st Continental Light Dragoons were reassigned to the Southern Department on 8 November 1778, when the Corps of Continental Light Dragoons was broken up as an organization.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The regiment was officially reorganized on 1 January 1781, consisting of four mounted and two dismounted troops.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] It was redesignated as the 1st Legionary Corps.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Captain Samuel Van Leer was also a member of this regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] On 2 November 1782, reflecting an amalgamation that had occurred in the spring of 1780, the unit was consolidated with the 3rd Legionary Corps, maintaining five troops.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The new unit was designated 1st Legionary Corps.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The regiment saw action at the Battle of Brandywine, Battle of Germantown and the Battle of Guilford Court House.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The regiment was disbanded on November 15, 1783, at Winchester, Virginia.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The **2nd Canadian Regiment** (1776–1783), also known as **Congress's Own** or **Hazen's Regiment**, was an Extra Continental regiment of the American Patriots' Continental Army, consisting primarily of volunteers from the Province of Quebec.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] It was authorized on January 20, 1776 under the command of Colonel Moses Hazen.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] All or part of the regiment saw action at Staten Island, Brandywine, Germantown and the Siege of Yorktown.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Most of its non-combat time was spent in and around New York City as part of the forces monitoring the British forces occupying that city.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment was disbanded on November 15, 1783 at West Point, New York.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment was one of a small number of Continental Army regiments that was the direct responsibility of the Continental Congress (most regiments were funded and supplied by a specific state).
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Commanded by Colonel (later Brigadier General) Moses Hazen for its entire existence, the regiment was originally made up of volunteers and refugees from Quebec who supported the rebel cause during the disastrous invasion of Canada.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Hazen and his staff were later authorized by Congress to recruit in other areas to supplement their ranks.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Late in 1775, Colonel James Livingston raised and commanded a regiment of Canadians that fought at St.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Jean, Quebec, in support of General Montgomery's 1775 invasion of Quebec.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Livingston's 300 Canadians, along with about 50 Americans, were instrumental in the fall of Fort Chambly during that engagement.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Livingston's regiment, which was not formalized by Montgomery until November 1775, also participated in the action at Quebec.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On January 3, 1776, Congress commissioned him Colonel, and his organization became known as the Canadian Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Moses Hazen had served as a lieutenant in the 44th Regiment during the French and Indian War and was receiving a half-pay pension for his British service.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] In 1775, while he was living on this plus the income from his estate in St.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Jean, Quebec, the colonial army invaded.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Nevertheless, Hazen was arrested by the British on suspicion of spying for the Americans.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] He was held a prisoner for 54 days, until he was finally released by General Montgomery after the fall of Montreal in November.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Hazen then joined the American cause, and took part in the battle of Quebec.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Following the American failure to take the city, Hazen and Edward Antill, an American expatriate, traveled to Philadelphia to report on the battle.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Congress partially compensated Hazen by establishing the 2nd Canadian Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] He accepted the command, thus forfeiting his British half-pay.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Antill was made lieutenant colonel of the regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Although John Duggan, one of Livingston's captains, had been promised a regiment by Benedict Arnold, Hazen and Antill reached Philadelphia before Duggan, and Hazen smeared his name in his effort to get command of the regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On January 20, 1776, Congress authorized the 2nd Canadian Regiment with an allowed maximum strength of 1,000.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] It would consist of four battalions (5 companies each), the only oversized regiment in the Continental Army.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] It was assigned to the Army's Canadian Department, and was organized by Hazen on February 10, 1776, at Montreal, to be recruited from the Richelieu and St.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Over the next two months, Hazen and Antill recruited in those areas, until early April, when the recruiting funds dried up, raising about 250 men.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] During much of the war, the 2nd Canadian Regiment was known as Congress's Own Regiment, and Livingston's command continued to be known as the Canadian Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Greatly depleted by its five years of service, Livingston's regiment was disbanded in the reorganization of the Continental Army on January 1, 1781.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Its Canadian elements were assigned to Hazen's command, which was then redesignated as the Canadian Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment was first assigned to garrison duty in and around Montreal, which was under Major General David Wooster's command.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] In March 1776, Wooster went to Quebec City to assume command of the army there; Hazen was temporarily placed in command of the forces at Montreal until Benedict Arnold arrived from Quebec in April.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Arnold then assigned the regiment to guard duty at Fort Chambly, where it remained until the American retreat in June 1776.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On July 2, the Canadian Department was disbanded, and regiment was reassigned to the Northern Department.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment was at Fort Ticonderoga in July 1776, Albany in September, and then Fishkill, New York, for winter quarters.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] By the time the regiment reached Albany, its strength had dropped to about 100.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On November 12, the regiment was assigned to the Highlands Department.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] It was reorganized on January 1, 1777, to consist of four battalions (20 companies), and Hazen was given permission to recruit "at large" – that is, he was allowed to recruit from any states, not just Quebec.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] These recruitment efforts met with mixed success, as most states had been assigned quotas for troop recruitment to fill their line companies, and thus preferred to have men enter those commands rather than Hazen's.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On January 8, the regiment was assigned to the Main Army.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment was at Princeton, New Jersey, as early as May 19, 1777, where it was assigned on May 22 to the 2nd Maryland Brigade of the Main Army.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] In early August the regiment, brigaded as part of General John Sullivan's Division, was encamped at Hanover, New Jersey.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Several of the regiment's companies participated in the Battle of Staten Island on August 22, 1777.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Its losses included 8 officers and 40 men, with the captured including Antill and Captain James Herron.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Antill would not be exchanged until November 10, 1780.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Sullivan's division then marched south to join Washington's army in the defense of Philadelphia.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On September 11, 1777, a battalion of 200 of Hazen's men was sent a mile north of Jones's Ford to cover Wistar's Ford, and a second battalion of 200 men was posted at Buffington's Ford about a mile north of Wistar's Ford, situated just below the forks of the Brandywine Creek.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Hazen's troops spotted British troops in a flanking maneuver and crossing the Brandywine River.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] They sent a report of this movement to George Washington, who initially did not believe this intelligence despite its corroboration by Lieutenant Colonel James Ross.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment lost 4 officers and 73 men in the battle.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Still under Sullivan's command, the regiment participated in the Battle of Germantown on October 4, 1777.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The British were encamped at Germantown northwest of Philadelphia.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On the evening of October 3 General Washington ordered his troops, encamped at Skippack Creek on the north side of the Schuylkill River, to march 17 miles (27 km) as part of a planned surprise attack on the British at daybreak.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The Americans would then descend upon Germantown from the north in four columns, under the commands of Generals Sullivan, Greene, Armstrong and Smallwood, along four main roads leading into Germantown.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The main effort of the advance was to be General Sullivan leading the column on the right and General Nathanael Greene on the left.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Sullivan's column, with the Continental troops of his own division and others, was to advance down Germantown Road against Howe's center.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment was part of the platoon of the advance party that first entered Germantown before the battle became general.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Unbeknownst to Washington, the columns of Greene and Smallwood got lost.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Washington himself accompanied Sullivan's force and, at 5 am, ordered him to launch the assault.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The leading element of Sullivan's column, General Thomas Conway's brigade, attacked the British 2d Light Infantry battalion, which had been reinforced by the British 40th Regiment of Foot under command of Lieutenant-Colonel Thomas Musgrave.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment formed part of Sullivan's early attack on the British; its losses were 3 officers and 19 men.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On December 21, 1777, the regiment and a detachment of the Maryland Line under the command of General William Smallwood (the 2nd Maryland Brigade) arrived at Wilmington, Delaware, to protect the city from the British.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] They encamped at the present-day Brandywine Park in Wilmington.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The highlight of this time included Smallwood's capture of the British armed brigantine *Symmetry* on December 30.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] This ship was laden with supplies, including winter clothing, en route to the British in Philadelphia.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On January 24, 1778, Washington ordered Hazen's regiment to Albany, New York, transferring it from the 2nd Maryland Brigade to the Northern Department.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The objective was a planned invasion of Quebec.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Hazen was assigned to the deputy quartermaster's post for the expedition, which was anticipated to involve 2,500 men.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The effort was troubled by supply and manpower difficulties, suspended in February, and then called off by Congress in March.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment was then reassigned to the Highlands Department on April 4 and ordered to West Point.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment was relieved July 22 from the Highlands Department and assigned to the New Hampshire Brigade, an element of the Main Army.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] In July 1778 the regiment was sent to White Plains to help guard New York City.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] At White Plains, Hazen proposed a new potential invasion route to Quebec.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] This route went from Newbury in the New Hampshire Grants (present-day Vermont), where Hazen owned property, to Saint Francis, Quebec.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On July 12, Hazen departed Newbury to scout the route.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] By July 25, he had returned to White Plains; the effort was abandoned for the time being because the manpower was needed in the New York area.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] That summer, low manpower in Hazen's regiment caused Washington to consider disbanding it; the regiment's size had dropped to 522, and Washington was concerned over an excessively large number of officers (33) in the regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Hazen successfully argued for retention of the regiment, and noted that the large number of officers was needed because companies from the regiment were often detached to other units for service.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] During the autumn a large shipment of clothing and shoes arrived from France.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] After a lottery was held in October, Hazen's regiment were issued the uniform of brown coats faced with red.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] In November, the regiment was ordered to Connecticut where it encamped at Redding for winter quarters.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] In March 1779 the regiment was reassigned to the Northern Department, and marched to Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] From Springfield they marched to Charlestown, New Hampshire and picked up clothing and supplies.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] They arrived in what was called the Coös Country of northern New Hampshire in May, and were tasked to build a road now known as the Bayley-Hazen Military Road from the Connecticut River to St.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Hazen had been secretly ordered to the area by Washington in April.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Along with a large portion of Colonel Timothy Bedel's Regiment and Major Benjamin Whitcomb's New Hampshire rangers, they began to extend the road, a portion of which had been constructed in 1776 under the direction of Colonel Jacob Bayley.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Hazen's objective was to extend a road in a northwest direction following the general path of an old Cohâssiac Indian trail from Lower Coös to St.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The road cut through the heavily forested Upper Connecticut Valley in an area of the New Hampshire Grants that was then known as Upper Coös, but is today known as Vermont's Northeast Kingdom.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The village of Peacham became the base of operations for the military road project.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The road actually started at the town of Wells River on the Connecticut River just north of Newbury.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Blockhouses were built at Peacham, Cabot, Walden and Greensboro.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Hazen made requisition upon the selectmen of the river towns to provide teams for the movement of his stores.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Wells were dug at various points, swamps were bridged with logs and the road made passable for teams.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Hazen encamped for some time on the present site of Lowell village, and he called the place "the camp at the end of the road", although the road's actual terminus was some miles further on.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The road crossed the Vermont Piedmont—rolling hills and valleys with isolated mountains.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On June 22 it was reported that Hazen with half his men were within 40 miles (64 km) of St.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment was recalled to the New York area in August; as a result, the road was never completed.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] A total of 54 miles (87 km) of road was built; the location where it ended is now known as Hazens Notch.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] In the fall, Hazen leveled charges of corruption and mismanagement against Isaac Tichenor, the deputy commissioner of purchases at Coös, General Bayley, the deputy quartermaster-general, and Matthew Lyons, the deputy commissioner of issues.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] His regiment were poorly supplied the whole summer at Coös, supplies of beef arrived spoiled, and Hazen had to send his men into the fields to help with the harvest so they could eat.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] In October 1779 the regiment was ordered to Peekskill, New York, and on November 25 it was assigned to Hand's Brigade in the Main Army.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] They spent the winter at Morristown, New Jersey, where they experienced severe shortages of food.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The site, known as "Jockey Hollow", is in the Morristown National Historical Park.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On January 14, 1780, the regiment participated in a "commando" raid of Staten Island planned in secrecy by General Washington and led by Lord Stirling.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The object of the raid was a surprise attack on the enemy at the Watering Place Redoubts and to secure provisions.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Preparations for the raid called for British attention to be focused on Irvine's detachment in the vicinity of Elizabethtown, while the 2nd Canadian marched to Connecticut Farms (present-day Union).
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Meanwhile, Steward's detachment would advance onto Staten Island, and Stirling's forces would then push to Richmond, in the center of Staten Island, where they would surprise enemy troops.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Lord Stirling had intelligence that the enemy had a force of about 1,000 men, with the main body in huts near the Watering Place Redoubts.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] These were three British circular redoubts, double-abatised, with about 200 men each, located at present-day Fort Hill Circle in St.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Around midnight on January 14, loaded with cannon and 1,500–3,000 troops, American forces crossed over the frozen ice of the Kill Van Kull waterway from Elizabethtown Point on 500 sleds.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] It was a starry night, and Loyalist spies had warned the British of the American approach.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] As a result, the Americans found the British on the posts and alert.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] With the element of surprise gone, and conditions extremely cold, the raid was aborted.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] American troops suffered minor frostbite injuries but brought back 17 prisoners, as well as some horses and camp supplies.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] In the spring of 1780, the regiment was subjected to a thorough inspection by Baron von Steuben, and was found to be "well taken care of".
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Von Steuben made recommendations as a result of his inspections (which covered much of the Continental Army) that resulted in the merging of the 1st and 2nd Canadian regiments in 1781.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment spent the summer of 1780 at King's Ferry, New York.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Regimental orderly books show that it was at Morristown, Bryant's Tavern, Ramapo and Preakness between April 23 and July 26.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On August 1 the regiment was reassigned from Hand's Brigade to the New Hampshire Brigade of the Main Army.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] This brigade was to be under the command of Enoch Poor, but its command was ultimately given to Hazen, although Hazen was not promoted to brigadier general.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On August 23, von Steuben arrested Hazen for halting his brigade on a march without permission.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The army was on the march from Tappan to the Liberty Pole, a pre-war landmark located near Englewood, when Hazen halted the march for his troops to drink water.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Hazen was acquitted of the charges, and promptly countercharged von Steuben with conduct unbecoming an officer over the incident; von Steuben apologized.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Following the capture of British spy John André and the defection of Benedict Arnold to the British in September 1780, one hundred of Hazen's soldiers, under command of Lieutenant William Torrey, were detailed to be present at André's hanging on October 2, at Tappan, New York.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] In the fall of 1780 the regiment was headquartered at Nelson's Point in Garrison, New York, directly across the Hudson River from West Point, before entering winter quarters at Fishkill, New York, in November.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Reid also made complaints against Hazen, which were heard and dismissed in a November 1780 court martial.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Hazen had Reid arrested and confined to quarters afterwards; a long court martial (running from December 1780 to February 1781) resulted in Reid's conviction on two counts and a public reprimand by General Washington.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Regimental orderly books show that during these periods the regiment had operations at Orangetown, Steeprapie and West Point between September 16 and November 19, and at West Point from October 5 to March 5, 1781.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On January 1, 1781, in accordance with von Steuben's recommendations, the 1st Canadian Regiment was disbanded.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The Canadian members were reassigned to the 2nd Regiment, which was then designated as the Canadian Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Most foreign volunteers were also assigned to the regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Hazen and part of the regiment participated in a raid on January 22 led by Lieutenant Colonel William Hull.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Hull raided a position held by a Loyalist corps under Lieutenant Colonel Oliver De Lancey Sr. that was at Morrisania (in the present-day Bronx).
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The Americans burned the enemy's barracks, captured 52 prisoners, and took large supplies of ammunition and forage.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Hazen's men were assigned to cover their retreat.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] About 1,000 British troops pursued Hull's men beyond a point where Hazen and his men were concealed.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] A skirmish took place, with British losing about 35 men.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On June 1, the regiment was sent from the West Point–Fishkill area to Albany and the Mohawk River valley to guard against an expected British attack.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] For this action it was reassigned from the Highlands Department to the Northern Department.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment arrived at Albany on June 5, and spent most of the month patrolling in the Mohawk River valley against an attack that never came.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] When the perceived threat subsided, the regiment was immediately ordered to return to West Point.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On June 29, Hazen was finally given a brevet promotion to brigadier general.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On August 10, 1781, the Canadian Regiment was reassigned from the Northern Department to the Main Army.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On August 19, Washington used the regiment to feint preparations for an attack on New York.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment withdrew, and held near Kakiat for three days from August 22–25.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment then went down the Hudson River and joined the army on the way to Yorktown.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] At midnight on September 2, 270 of the regiment and other units arrived at Christiana Bridge over the Delaware.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The units unloaded the boats and transported supplies for the Continental Army to Elk Landing during the three days before the boat carriages arrived.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On September 24, Hazen was given command of the second brigade of Marquis de Lafayette's Light Division, to which the Canadian Regiment (now under the command of Lieutenant Colonel Antill) was assigned.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] After cantonment at Williamsburg, the regiment arrived at Yorktown on September 28.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Roughly a quarter of the regiment participated in the siege, and was involved in the October 14 attacks on the British redoubts.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] According to Lafayette's own account the Americans did not fire a gun, but used only the bayonet.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The brigades of light infantry under Generals Peter Muhlenberg and Hazen "advanced with perfect discipline and wonderful steadiness.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The battalion of Colonel Vose deployed on the left.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment was reassigned from Hazen's Brigade to the Middle Department on December 6, 1781.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On this date, a portion of the regiment went to Lancaster, Pennsylvania, where they guarded prisoners taken at Yorktown.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] They were on this detail for 10 months with prisoners under guard at Lancaster, York and Reading.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The most notable prisoner under Hazen's watch during this time was 20-year-old Captain Charles Asgill.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] On May 3, 1782, upon orders by Washington, he was selected to hang in retaliation for the brutal summary execution of American Captain Joshua Huddy by the British.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] In November 1782 his life was spared after heartrending correspondence by his family and intervention by the Queen of France.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] In June 1782 Hazen again had James Reid arrested on charges including disobedience and conduct unbecoming an officer.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The court martial, held in December, resulted in a mistrial, with Hazen alleging bias on the part of the presiding judge advocate.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] After additional hearings, Reid was ultimately acquitted of the charges.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] In November 1782, the regiment was moved to Pompton, New Jersey, for winter quarters.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Its duties during this time included the interdiction of trade between the countryside and the British in New York City.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] In June 1783, with the peace nearly finalized, much of the regiment was furloughed.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] At the same time it was transferred to the Highland Department.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Pursuant to a Resolution of Congress of May 26, 1783, 300 soldiers were discharged on June 9.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] However, members of the regiment refused to depart, whether on furlough or discharge, until they received their pay.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Members of the regiment that remained were ordered to march to Washington's cantonment near New Windsor.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment was reorganized into two companies on June 30 and was completely disbanded on November 15, 1783, at West Point, New York.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] Because the Canadians in the regiment were unable to return to their homes, many of them settled in camps near Albany and Fishkill, where they subsisted on handouts from Congress.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] General Hazen appealed to Congress to give them land grants, but this effort failed.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The state of New York eventually granted Hazen and a number of his men land in the northern part of the state near Lake Champlain.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-canadian-regiment] The regiment's authorized strength was 1,000 men.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] The **2nd Continental Artillery Regiment** also known as **Lamb's Continental Artillery Regiment** was authorized on 1 January 1777 as Colonel John Lamb's Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] As originally constituted, the regiment included 12 artillery companies from New York, Connecticut, and Pennsylvania.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] The bulk of the regiment served in the Hudson Highlands, though some companies fought with George Washington's main army from 1777 to 1779.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] On 10 August 1779 the unit was renamed the 2nd Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Two companies were transferred to the 4th Continental Artillery Regiment on 1 January 1781 to form a 10-company regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] In August 1781 the regiment was reassigned to the main army in time to fight at the Siege of Yorktown.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] The regiment returned to the Hudson Highlands in the summer of 1782.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] It was reduced to two companies in June 1783.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] The regiment was dissolved on 1 January 1784 except for one company which remained in the regular army.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Lamb's Continental Artillery Regiment became part of the Continental Army on 1 January 1777.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] During the spring of 1777, the regiment was formed around a core of three existing New York artillery companies under Captains Andrew Moodie, Sebastian Bauman, and John Doughty.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Moodie's company was originally authorized on 30 June 1775 as Captain John Lamb's company.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] It formed in New York City in July and August 1775.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Part of the unit went on Benedict Arnold's expedition to Quebec where it was captured at the Battle of Quebec on 31 December 1775.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] The rump of the unit became Captain-lieutenant Isaiah Wool's Artillery Detachment and served first in the New York Department.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] On 20 January 1776 the unit was assigned to the Canadian Department.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] On 2 July 1776 it was reassigned to the Northern Department and it joined Lamb's Regiment on 1 January 1777.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Bauman's company was authorized on 28 October 1775 and recruited in New York.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Organized in New York City from December 1775 to May 1776, it was assigned to Washington's main army on 13 April 1776.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Bauman's company became part of Lamb's Regiment on 1 January 1777.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Doughty's company was authorized on 6 January 1776 as the New York Provincial Company of Artillery.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Assembled at New York City in the late winter of 1776, it joined George Washington's main army on 17 June 1776.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Doughty's company joined Lamb's Regiment on 17 March 1777.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] On 26 December 1776, Bauman commanded his 80-man company and three cannons at the Battle of Trenton.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Together with Captain Alexander Hamilton's New York battery and Thomas Forrest's Pennsylvania battery, Bauman's company unlimbered on high ground at the head of King and Queen Streets.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] The American artillery proceeded to overwhelm the Hessian gunners manning two cannons on King Street, and laid down an effective zone of fire.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] After Trenton, command of Hamilton's company passed to Doughty.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Additional companies were authorized to make a total of 12 companies.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Added to the three original companies were four new companies recruited from New Haven and Fairfield Counties, Connecticut.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Three new companies came from New York state and two new companies came from Philadelphia, Pennsylvania and Montgomery County, Pennsylvania.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] The three original companies and the two Pennsylvania companies assembled at Morristown, New Jersey.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] The three newly raised New York companies organized at Peekskill, New York, while the four Connecticut companies organized at New Haven, Connecticut and Peekskill.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Lamb went to Canada with Richard Montgomery and was captured at Quebec.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Though paroled a few days later, he wasn't formally exchanged until January 1777.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] He was promoted colonel of the artillery regiment on 1 January 1777.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] On 28 April 1777 he was wounded at Campo Hill during the Danbury Raid while trying to stop a bayonet attack with three cannons.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] In early 1778 Lamb became embroiled in a dispute over seniority, but remained in command of the regiment throughout the war.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] He was the artillery commander at West Point, New York in 1779 and 1780, including at the time when Benedict Arnold attempted to betray the fort to the British.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] The evening after Arnold's treason, Washington ordered Lamb to assume command over the key strategic position of King's Ferry, New York because he did not fully trust another officer.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] On 12 June 1777, Lamb's artillery regiment was assigned to the Highlands Department.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] However, some units fought with the main army in the Philadelphia Campaign.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] The regiment's Captain James Lee fought at the Siege of Fort Mifflin in November 1777.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Like Lamb, Eleazer Oswald was captured at Quebec and not exchanged until January 1777 when he was commissioned lieutenant colonel in Lamb's Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Oswald served as Charles Lee's chief artillery officer at the Battle of Monmouth on 28 June 1778.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Though his actions at Monmouth were praised, Oswald resigned from the army soon after the battle because he was miffed at being passed over for promotion.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] On 10 August 1779 the four artillery regiments were numbered.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Two boards of generals ruled that neither Lamb's Regiment nor John Crane's Continental Artillery Regiment could trace their lineage to Knox's Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Therefore, Charles Harrison's Continental Artillery Regiment was named the 1st Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Lamb and Crane drew lots and Lamb's regiment became the 2nd Continental Artillery Regiment while Crane's regiment was renamed the 3rd Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Since it was the last regiment to enter the Continental Army, Thomas Proctor's Continental Artillery Regiment was designated the 4th Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Lamb was artillery commander at West Point in 1779 and 1780.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] The 2nd Artillery was reorganized into 10 companies on 1 January 1781.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] At this time, the companies of Captains Andrew Porter and Jonas Simonds transferred into the 4th Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] The regiment was assigned to the main army on 28 August 1781.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] Lamb took his regiment south for the Yorktown campaign.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] At the Siege of Yorktown in the fall of 1781, the 2nd Artillery numbered 225 men.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] On 24 August 1782 the 2nd Artillery was reassigned to the Highlands Department.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] The regiment was reduced to two companies on 11 June 1783 and disbanded on 1 January 1784.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] However, Doughty's company remained in the United States army at West Point.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-artillery-regiment] The 1st Battalion of the 5th Field Artillery Regiment can trace its lineage to Doughty's company.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-light-dragoons] The **2nd Continental Light Dragoons**, also known as **Sheldon's Horse** after Colonel Elisha Sheldon, was commissioned by the Continental Congress on 12 December 1776, and was first mustered at Wethersfield, Connecticut, in March 1777 for service with the Continental Army.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-light-dragoons] The regiment consisted of four troops from Connecticut, one troop each largely from Massachusetts and New Jersey, and two companies of light infantry.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-light-dragoons] The unit almost never served as a whole.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-light-dragoons] Usually individual troops were assigned as necessary.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-light-dragoons] The regiment performed numerous raids from whaleboats against British and Loyalist targets on Long Island.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-light-dragoons] Some of the successful raids captured Fort St.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-light-dragoons] George, Fort Slongo and Lloyd's Neck, Long Island.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-light-dragoons] Elements from the unit comprised George Washington's personal bodyguard.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-light-dragoons] The regiment's main patrol areas during the war were in Southern Connecticut and New York, where they intercepted British supplies and fought off bands of Loyalist partisans who preyed on local citizens.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-light-dragoons] This duty earned them the nickname "Watchdogs of the Highlands".
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-light-dragoons] They also earned the sobriquet "Washington's Eyes", likely because of their spy work.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-light-dragoons] Major Benjamin Tallmadge became a spy master who ran one of the most successful spy rings of the war, able to infiltrate the British military command in New York city.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-light-dragoons] On 1 January 1781, the regiment was reorganized by the dismounting of two of its six troops and re-designated the *2nd Legionary Corps*.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-light-dragoons] The regiment was furloughed 9 June 1783, at Newburgh, New York and discharged on 20 November 1783, by proclamation of General Washington.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/2nd-continental-light-dragoons] The 2nd Light Dragoons are prominent in Colonel John Trumbull's paintings of the American Revolution.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] The **3rd Continental Artillery Regiment** also known as **Crane's Continental Artillery Regiment** became part of the Continental Army on January 1, 1777, as Colonel John Crane's Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] The regiment was made up of 12 artillery companies from Massachusetts and Rhode Island, including some companies that had served in Henry Knox's Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] The regiment served with George Washington's main army.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] Three artillery companies in Ebenezer Stevens' Provisional Artillery Battalion had a separate existence in the Northern Department until the end of 1778 when they rejoined the regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] On 10 August 1779 the unit was redesignated the 3rd Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] The regiment was reorganized with 10 companies on 1 January 1781 after the transfer of several companies to another artillery regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] The unit was reassigned to the Highlands Department in August 1782.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] The regiment was rebuilt on a four company establishment in June 1783.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] The 3rd Artillery was disbanded on 1 January 1784 at West Point, New York.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] Two boards of generals determined that neither John Lamb's Continental Artillery Regiment nor Crane's Regiment could trace their lineage to Knox's Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] Being the last regiment to enter the Continental Army, Thomas Proctor's Continental Artillery Regiment was numbered the 4th Continental Artillery Regiment.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] Washington's artillery chief, Henry Knox wanted to have four 3-pound or 6-pound cannons attached to each infantry brigade.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] Knox preferred the handier French 4-pound cannon, he had to give up his plan to adopt it because too much ammunition and equipment for the 3- and 6-pound guns were still available.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] Knox created an artillery park of two 24-pound cannons, four 12-pound cannons, four 8-inch howitzers, eight 5.5-inch howitzers, and 10 smaller field guns.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] Rotating between the infantry brigades, the artillery park, and garrisons, the artillery companies with the main army received training in these various areas.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] Knox's tactical doctrine required his gunners to direct their fire on infantry targets and avoid artillery duels.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-artillery-regiment] This tactic proved highly effective at the Battle of Monmouth.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] The **3rd Continental Light Dragoons** (CLD), also known as **Baylor's Horse** or **Lady Washington's Horse**, was a mounted regiment of the Continental Army raised on January 1, 1777, at Morristown, New Jersey.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] The regiment saw action at the Battle of Brandywine, the Battle of Germantown and the Battle of Guilford Court House.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] The regiment was surprised on the night of September 27, 1778, while sleeping in barns near Old Tappan, New Jersey, in close proximity to British positions.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] Referred to by the Continentals as the "Baylor Massacre", at least 67 men were casualties and 70 horses killed.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] Among the captured was the regimental commander, Lt.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] George Baylor, who was replaced on November 20, 1778, by Lt.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] William Washington, transferred from the 4th Continental Light Dragoons.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] In 1779, while recruiting and remounting, the regiment rescued James Wilson during the "Fort Wilson Riot".
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] The 3rd CLD was posted to the Southern department on November 1, 1779.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] Losses of 15 killed, 17 wounded, and 100 men captured along with 83 horses in a night attack by British Lt.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] Banastre Tarleton on April 14, 1780, led to the unofficial amalgamation of the regiment with the 1st Continental Light Dragoons, commonly known as the "1st and 3rd Light Dragoons" as Washington deferred to his friend and senior, Lt.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] Anthony White, whom he had served under in the 4th CLD.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] Washington resumed command of the unit on May 6, 1780, when it was attacked on the Santee River and White captured.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] In the 1781 campaign, Washington and his men distinguished themselves in mounted charges at the Battle of Cowpens in January, the Battle of Guilford Court House in March, and the Battle of Eutaw Springs in September.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] At Eutaw Springs Washington was pinned under his fallen mount, bayoneted, and captured.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] Captain William Parsons, the senior surviving officer, commanded the corps until Lt-Col.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] Baylor was exchanged in June 1782 and resumed command.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] When the companies of the 4th CLD were parceled out during the siege of Yorktown, the 1st and 3rd accepted its few remaining mounted troopers.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] The regiment was officially merged into the 1st Legionary Corps on November 2, 1782, with the consolidated unit of five troops designated the 1st Legionary Corps.
[src:2nd-continental-artillery-regiment/3rd-continental-light-dragoons] A member of the 3rd Continental Dragoons was Maryland Congressman Philip Stuart.
